Energy policy:
the facts must cost more than the dogmas
If there is a topic that cannot talk each other bearing in mind short term considerations or simply thinking about the emotions, it is the energy policy.
The availability and the cost of the electricity influence straight the purchasing power and the competitiveness of the companies.
It turns out to be suitable that an electoral meeting is the moment to reflect on such questions and on the place of the nuclear energy.
The debate will only turn out to be useful if he studies the set of the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base its opinion on objective facts, on rational information.
Now when we are 7.000 million persons in the planet, the demographic evolution will suppose the duplication of the electrical demand before 2050, unless it is deprived to an enormous part of the world population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to relieve the every time major scarcity of the fossil resources to keep on producing electricity continuously, without forgetting the imperious need to reduce the greenhouse effect gas emission to fight against the climate change, a topic that has disappeared of the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not modify any of these parameters.
That's why, Germany remains alone in its decision to resign from the nuclear energy.
This is not the case either of Belgium, which his submits to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or of Switzerland, which only has to construct for an object head offices of last generation.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, Czech Republic, Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, for quoting some examples, go forward with determination with its projects.
The United States, from his part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, recapturing the construction of a head office interrupted after the accident of Three Mile Island.
If the German model, based on the renewable energies, presents himself sometimes as an example, the reality goes against such a speech.
The election of Berlin is going to suppose an increase of the price of the electricity, a major energy dependence for the increased need for imported gas, in particular of Russia, an increase of the emission of CO2 for the coal and gas head offices construction.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be evident.
It must be pondered on the case of Denmark.
Champion of Europe in the wind sector, of which it obtains 30 % of its electricity, also is one of the big users of coal and of gas due to the intermittence of the wind; for this reason, its emission of CO2 and price of its electricity are, respectively, 65 % and 50 % higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the steadfastness of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an invoice of electricity 40 % superior to that of the French hearths.
While in an encompassed economy the cost of the energy constitutes a key factor of the competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial utility in the national territory, the French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity of Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction of the nuclear energy would suppose a strong increase of the price of the electricity, what would reduce realism to the wonderful declarations on the restructuring of industry of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
It is a question of a price that the majority of the French refuses to pay and, in fact, they do not show opposition for beginning to this type of energy, as the surveys show.
Let's remember that the energy policy of our country has lost to construct an industrial sector with 125.000 positions of governing work and 410.000 indirect work places.
Extensively faced to the exportation, it includes a galaxy of pymes specializing on the international markets and that can create jobs not deslocalizables.
If France was deciding to leave the nuclear energy, there would suppose the sacrifice of big part of this SME and the loss of 6.000 million euros per year in French exports of equipment and nuclear services.
What electrician would entrust an EPR designed to work sixty years, when the destruction of its manufacturer is foreseen?
To solve the equation of the nuclear energy, it is necessary to admit that there does not exist a miraculous source of production of electricity, as a diabolical source does not exist either.
The development on the part of solutions Areva with low emission of CO2, nuclear and renewable, demonstrates the complementary character of the energy sources.
In case of the nuclear energy, it turns out to be essential to maintain the maximum safety level.
In France, we have a safety Authority that exercises a strict and transparent control both on the existing head offices and on the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with the safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, took place in a few normal operative conditions; it provoked consequences neither for the persons nor for the environment.
In Chernobil, the accident owed to the design of the reactor and to a few inexcusable human mistakes.
In Fukushima, some persons seem to forget that the accident owed to two natural disasters of a scope without precedents, who provoked the death of tens thousands of persons.
The nuclear sector will learn of this accident, as it did it of two previous ones.
Thanks to these progresses and a cooperation between the safety authorities, and the operators and French and German builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting to such phenomena.
While it is studied by all the electrical actors who want to construct a head office, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a big gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave free route to them to assume the leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It turns out to be indispensable and legitimate to look for the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to stop that the emotion, the dogmas and the maneuvers partisans were dominating such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
