But the experience demonstrates that, in fact, the immigrants are rather complementary that substitutes of the national workpeople and they exercise principally professions in sectors with absence of employment.
The slightly qualified immigrants are employed at sectors that do not attract workpeople national and most qualified in dynamic sectors where the formation does not satisfy the personnel demand.
A positive effect on the wages
In the same way that a surgeon would have difficulties of working in a country that it has lacking in anesthetists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants provokes that the arrival of the above mentioned influences positively the wages and the employment of the nationals.
Bearing in mind the previous thing, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1 % of the migratory flows supposes an increase of the long-term real wages of between 0,6 and 0,9 %.
