Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to return to the people the taste for the writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing in view of a sail.
The notebook Moleskine recognizes after itself easily, with its black rectangular pastas, its gum, its sheets of broken white color, like aged in the time.
Nevertheless, the notebooks Moleskine with the current aspect were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Way Way, based on Milan, decided in that moment to throw to the market a notebook of notes of design, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, at that time counsel of the company, took charge of the throwing of the new product.
The notebook is inspired in an ancient production skill, the thick chile sauce skin (skin of mole), which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, between other things, to cover the stools.
This type of notebook was much valued by the writers and the travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the XXth century", tells Maria Sebregondi, who since then turned into person in charge of the mark in Way Way.
And it reached the success.
Between 2006 and 2010, the sales increased in 26 %, up to reaching a volume of 12,7 million sold units.
Far there has stayed the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3.000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond the Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It turns out to be difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notes notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
As Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, of open spirit and cults.
